1.2: Adding day of the week and month information on the data¶

In [8]:
def date_to_weekday_str(date):
    days = {1: 'Monday',
           2: 'Tuesday',
           3: 'Wednesday',
           4: 'Thursday',
           5: 'Friday',
           6: 'Saturday',
           7: 'Sunday'}
    
    return days[date.isoweekday()]


df['weekday'] = df['order_date'].apply(date_to_weekday_str)
In [9]:
df['month'] = df['order_date'].dt.month_name()

1.3: Merging rows of the same order together in an one-hot manner.¶

E.g., if the dataset is (disregarding dates for the example):

Customer_id Item Name
1 A
2 B
3 A
1 B
2 C

The resulting dataset will be:

Customer_id A B C
1 1 1 0
2 0 1 1
3 1 0 0
In [10]:
data_rows = {}
#
# The key of each row is the <customer-id>-<date>.
# The value of each row is a list of 170 values, so
#  0    : customer_id
#  1    : date
#  2    : day of the week
#  3    : month
#  4-169: data items in one-hot encoding. E.g. if the i-th item has a value of 1,
#         then the i-th item was part of this order. Otherwise its value is 0.
#


for index, row in df.iterrows():
    customer_id = row['customer_id']
    date        = row['order_date']
    weekday     = row['weekday']
    item        = row['item']
    
    key         = f"{customer_id}-{date.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')}"
    
    if key not in data_rows.keys():
            empty_row      = [0 for _ in range(len(item_categories)+4)]
            data_rows[key] = empty_row
            
    data_rows[key][0]             = f"{customer_id}"
    data_rows[key][1]             = date.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
    data_rows[key][2]             = weekday
    data_rows[key][3]             = row['month']
    item_col                      = item_categories.index(item)
    data_rows[key][item_col+4]    = 1
    
    
print(f"Parsed {len(data_rows)} rows (orders)")

Parsed 14963 rows (orders)

def count_items_in_order(row):
    items     = row[item_categories]
    num_items = items.sum()
    return num_items

In [15]:
def calculate_item_frequencies(df):
    item_frequencies = df.sum()
    item_frequencies_list = [(item_name, frequency, item_categories.index(item_name)) for item_name, frequency in item_frequencies.items()]
    return item_frequencies_list

item_frequencies = calculate_item_frequencies(df2[item_categories])

max_item, max_frequency, _ = max(item_frequencies, key=lambda x: x[1])
min_item, min_frequency, _ = min(item_frequencies, key=lambda x: x[1])


print(f"Most frequently bough item: {max_item} ({max_frequency} appearances in orders)")
print(f"Most frequently bough item: {min_item} ({min_frequency} appearances in orders)")

def plot_item_frequencies_bar(item_frequencies_list):
    # Sort the item frequencies list by frequency in descending order
    sorted_items = sorted(item_frequencies_list, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)

    items, frequencies, _ = zip(*sorted_items)

    plt.bar(items, frequencies)
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.xlabel('Items (in arbitrary order)')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('Item Frequencies')
    #plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.grid(axis='y')
    #plt.yscale('log')
    plt.show()
    
    
plot_item_frequencies_bar(item_frequencies)

group_data_rows = {}
#
# The key of each row is the <customer-id>-<date>.
# The value of each row is a list of 170 values, so
#  0    : customer_id
#  1    : date
#  2    : day of the week
#  3    : month
#  4-21 : data items in one-hot encoding. E.g. if the i-th item has a value of 1,
#         then the i-th item was part of this order. Otherwise its value is 0.
#


for index, row in df.iterrows():
    customer_id = row['customer_id']
    date        = row['order_date']
    weekday     = row['weekday']
    item        = row['item']
    
    key         = f"{customer_id}-{date.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')}"
    
    if key not in group_data_rows.keys():
            empty_row            = [0 for _ in range(len(group_categories)+4)]
            group_data_rows[key] = empty_row
            
    group_data_rows[key][0]             = f"{customer_id}"
    group_data_rows[key][1]             = date.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
    group_data_rows[key][2]             = weekday
    group_data_rows[key][3]             = row['month']
    group_name                          = groups[item]
    item_col                            = group_categories.index(group_name)
    group_data_rows[key][item_col+4]   += 1
    
    
print(f"Parsed {len(group_data_rows)} rows (orders)")

def count_groups_in_order(row):
    items     = row[group_categories]
    num_items = (items>0).sum()
    return num_items

def calculate_group_frequencies(df):
    group_frequencies = (df>0).sum()
    groupfrequencies_list = [(group_name, frequency) for group_name, frequency in group_frequencies.items()]
    return groupfrequencies_list

group_frequencies = calculate_group_frequencies(df3[group_categories])
group_frequencies = sorted(group_frequencies, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)

for group_name, group_freq in group_frequencies:
    print(f"Group {group_name:<18}: Found in {group_freq:4d} orders.")
    
group_names, frequencies = zip(*group_frequencies)

plt.xlabel('Group Names')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.title('Group Frequencies')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')

4.4: Divide the age values into bins to reduce the final number of columns¶

In [34]:
num_age_groups = 10
age_range = max_age - min_age + 1
group_width = age_range / num_age_groups

age_group_boundaries = [min_age + i * group_width for i in range(num_age_groups)]
age_group_boundaries.append(max_age)

def assign_age_group_index(age):
    for i, boundary in enumerate(age_group_boundaries[:-1], start=1):
        if age <= boundary:
            return i
    return 10  # If age exceeds the maximum boundary, assign it to the last group

df3['age_groups'] = df3['age_years'].apply(assign_age_group_index)

4.5: Convert the age groups in one hot encoding to produce another dataset for Weka¶

In [37]:
df4 = df3.copy()

age_groups        = df4['age_groups']
age_group_columns = [f'Age_group_{i+1}' for i in range(num_age_groups)]

# Create K new columns initialized with 0s
for age_group_column in age_group_columns:
    df4[age_group_column] = 0

# Set the value of the corresponding bin column to 1 for each row
for idx, age_group in age_groups.items():
    df4.at[idx, f'Age_group_{age_group}'] = 1

def dataframe_to_ARFF(df, dataset_name, output_file):
    
    header = f"@relation {dataset_name}\n"
    
    for attribute_name in df.columns:
        header += f"@attribute {attribute_name.replace(' ','_')}" + " {,t}\n"
    
    header += "@data\n\n"
    

    with open(output_file, 'w') as f:
        
        f.write(header)
    
        i = 0
        for index, row in df.iterrows():
            row     = row.values
            row_str = ','.join(['?' if val == 0 else 't' for val in row])
            
            f.write(row_str + "\n")
            i += 1
        
        print(f"Wrote {i} data rows with {len(df.columns)} attributes to {output_file}.")

dataframe_to_ARFF(df2[item_categories], 'customerBuys', output_file)
dataframe_to_ARFF(df2[most_frequent_items], 'customerBuysFrequent', frequent_output_file)            
dataframe_to_ARFF(df3[group_categories], 'customerBuysGroups', group_output_file)
dataframe_to_ARFF(df4[age_group_columns+list(group_categories)], 'customerBuysAges', age_output_file)
